  "prompt": "Do people with Borderline Personality Disorder ever develop a fear of relationships or intimacy?",
  "response": "Yes, individuals with Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD) can develop a fear of relationships or intimacy. BPD is characterized by intense and unstable interpersonal relationships, self-image, and emotions. People with BPD often experience a deep fear of abandonment and struggle with feelings of rejection or perceived betrayal. This can lead to a pattern of avoiding relationships or intimacy as a means of self-protection. They might oscillate between craving closeness and pushing others away, which can make it difficult for them to maintain stable, healthy relationships. Therapy, especially Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT), can be beneficial in helping individuals with BPD learn to manage their fears and build more stable relationships.",
